threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a DDoS bot for MIPS-based Linux systems, characteristic of IoT malware. Upon execution, it daemonizes itself using a double-fork, establishes a connection with a Command and Control (C2) server, and announces its presence with an "INFECTED" banner. It then enters a loop to receive and execute commands. The bot is capable of launching numerous types of DDoS attacks, including UDP, TCP, HTTP, and various amplification attacks (NTP, SSDP, LDAP). It uses a large, hardcoded list of legitimate User-Agent strings to disguise HTTP flood traffic. For persistence, it attempts to manipulate system watchdog devices (`/dev/watchdog`, `/dev/misc/watchdog`) to prevent the compromised device from rebooting.
